    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1923-09-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1923-09-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="104"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d104">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.559/3</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Belgium</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Fletcher</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-09-10">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 10, 1923</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to the Department’s circular telegram
                    dated June 12, 1923, 3 P.M., forwarded from the American Embassy at Paris,
                    concerning the proposal for a treaty to be concluded between the United States
                    and Belgium with respect to the enforcement of prohibition on Belgian vessels
                    within American territorial waters and measures for stopping liquor smuggling,
                    the Department encloses for your information a copy of an instruction, dated
                    August 25, 1923, addressed to the American Embassy at London dealing with the
                        matter.<note n="36" xml:id="d104fn36">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_172">p. 172</ref>.</note>
                    Copies of the notes exchanged with the British Embassy concerning the <hi
                        rend="italic">Henry L. Marshall</hi> case referred to on page seven of the
                    enclosed instruction are forwarded herewith for your information.<note n="37"
                        xml:id="d104fn37">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_163">pp. 163</ref> and <ref
                            target="#pg_165">165</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>You will observe that the extract from the <hi rend="italic">Columbia Law
                        Review</hi> quoted in the enclosed instruction contains the following
                    statement regarding Belgian laws that deal with the extent of territorial
                    jurisdiction claimed by Belgium: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p rend="flushleft">“Belgium has a customs zone of six miles and a fisheries
                            zone of three geographic miles.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>The foot-note cites the following authorities in support of this statement: <pb
                        facs="0299" n="183" xml:id="pg_183"/>
                    <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“<hi rend="italic">Codes des Contributions directes douanes et accises de
                                la Belgique en vigueur</hi> [<hi rend="italic">au</hi>] <hi
                                rend="italic">1er Aout</hi> (1852) p. 621, in Crocker, <hi
                                rend="italic">op. cit.</hi>, p. 511.</p>
                        <p>“See 19 Hertslet, <hi rend="italic">op. cit</hi>. (1895) p. 115; Crocker,
                                <hi rend="italic">op. cit.</hi>, p. 512.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>[Here follows, <hi rend="italic">mutatis mutandis</hi>, the same text as in
                    instructions to the Chargé in France, September 10, 1923, beginning with “You
                    will submit,” printed on <ref target="#pg_180">pages 180</ref>–<ref
                        target="#pg_181">181</ref>.]</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Charles E. Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
